node.text: A true pioneer in both underwater filmmaking and shark research, Valerie Taylor is a living legend whose life’s work has become the basis for much of what we know about sharks today. Follow this daring ocean explorer’s trajectory from champion spearfisher to passionate shark protector in Playing With Sharks, now streaming on @disneyplus

node.text: Grand Caillou/Dulac, Louisiana, U.S.A.: Meet Chief Shirell, the first female chief of her southern Louisiana tribe. Her ancestors have lived on the land for hundreds of years, and they are now expected to be among the United States’ first climate refugees. Chief Shirell can’t stop the storms, but she is impacting the legacy of her ancestors, the lives of her community today and the future of her people.

node.text: Memphis, Tennessee, U.S.A.: Meet Kayla, who has dedicated her life to helping homeless transgender women of color in Memphis, Tennessee. Having experienced homelessness and violence herself, Kayla has created a safe community for these notoriously discriminated-against people. She is building more than two dozen houses across Memphis for transgender women who need safety and a place to call home.

node.text: Half Moon Bay, California, U.S.A.: Kelsey is driven by two passions: surfing and helping people through grief and trauma. After losing her twin sister to COVID-19, Kelsey turns her grief into impact by healing others through a special surf therapy program that she started for women suffering from the effects of human trafficking, domestic violence, sexual assault, grief and loss.

node.text:
Photos by Pete McBride @pedromcbride / Dust on snow:  Snowfields across the Rockies have become covered in dust in recent years—and the tea-colored snow doesn’t just mar scenic views. The dirt acts like a blanket on the snowpack, absorbing heat from the sun and melting the snow more quickly—up to six weeks earlier—than it would without the layer. 

Forty million people in the Colorado River Basin rely on sustained snowpack for drinking water and to irrigate 5.5 million acres of agricultural land. The American Southwest is enduring the 22nd year of the worst drought in about 500 years. This intense and widespread spell defies historical records and leaves meteorologists and water managers at a loss for how to predict the future. Scientists argue that the West is now experiencing “aridification”—a permanent transition to an “increasingly water-scarce environment.”

That combined with more oil and gas development, grazing, and off-road vehicle use can bring more erosion in fragile desert landscapes. It's led to a 60 percent increase in dust storms in the last two decades, about 48 a year. Some storms bring dust from as far away as the Sonoran Desert to the Great Basin and the Colorado Plateau, dropping it in the Rockies and coloring the once white mountains red, pink, or brown. For more on this story, click the link in our bio.

Photo by @paoloverzone / About 30 miles northwest of Barcelona, Can Mata landed on the fossil map in the early 1940s when Miquel Crusafont, namesake of the ICP (Institute of Paleontology Miquel Crusafont), discovered the partial mandible and teeth of a Miocene great ape at the site. Subsequent finds helped establish Can Mata as a  paleontological site. Despite that status, it also has operated legally as a landfill since the mid-1980s.

In the early 2000s, when site operator Cespa Waste Management wanted to dig new trash-holding cells at least 100 feet deep, the company was obliged under the Spanish law to make sure its machines weren’t crunching through fossils or burying them beneath mounds of trash. Cespa approached some fossil-spotting scientists to supervise the excavations, and they jumped at the chance. ICP director David Alba (pictured) has been making discoveries at Can Mata since he was a Ph.D. student. Among his early finds was Pierolapithecus catalaunicus, one of the most complete Miocene primate skeletons. “From the viewpoint of paleontological heritage, the dump is making a huge contribution to science,” Alba says. For more on this story, click the link in our bio. Follow @paoloverzone for more photos and stories.

node.text: Photo by @michaelchristopherbrown / A gathering of friends in the Topanga area of Los Angeles celebrate the "strawberry" moon on June 24, 2021, the first full moon after the solstice. According to the Old Farmer’s Almanac, which uses Native American names for the full moons, the term strawberry moon was used by the Algonquin, Ojibwe, Dakota, and Lakota peoples to signify the arrival and associated gathering of ripened strawberries.

node.text:
Photo by David Chancellor @chancellordavid / So what happens backstage? As a photographer, I’m drawn to capturing behind the scenes. Time and familiarity with those we work alongside can create a special kind of access and level of trust. For my project on the Reteti Elephant Sanctuary, the published images are extraordinarily powerful—but so are moments such as this one, when in the deep of night your sleeping partners just don’t want to sleep anymore. I’ve said it before, and I’ll say it again: I’m in awe of the work done by the elephant caregivers at Reteti. 

These orphan elephants often arrive from the most traumatic of 
circumstances, and within days, they're calm, trusting, and moving toward life, rather than slipping away from it. This story for National Geographic explored the underbelly of conservation funding during the time of COVID. Not everybody came out shining, but many sparkled brighter than I’d imagined possible, particularly when the lights were out and no one was looking. With huge thanks to all those who let me simply be in their lives over this unprecedented and complex time. Click the link in Nat Geo’s bio for more on this story.

node.text: Video by @joelsartore / Is that a shark with a really long nose? Nope, it’s an American paddlefish! The species dates back to the dinosaurs and lives in U.S. rivers, but it’s that huge rostrum where all the action is for this otherworldly, ancient creature. It’s actually an elaborate sensor, used by the fish both for navigation and to detect the faint electrical signals of the plankton the fish loves to eat. Once zooplankton are found, the paddlefish uses that shark-like tail to swim forward, mouth open, and strain enough of the tiny creatures to make a meal. And it can do all this in muddy water…at night. Amazing! Video taken @medicine_park_aquarium. To see a still shot of this species, follow me @joelsartore. #paddlefish #spoonbill #bigfish #PhotoArk #savetogether

Photo by @mattiasklumofficial / I photographed this Galápagos mockingbird as it inspected a Galápagos land iguana for ticks. The iguana, which can weigh more than eleven kilos (25 pounds), appears to invite the entrepreneurial bird, sometimes freezing all movement until the bird has finished feeding on the ticks that often cling to the lizard’s neck. Both the bird and the lizard benefit—symbiotic cooperation. Please check out @mattiasklumofficial to learn more about our projects around the world.
#protectbiodiversity #galapagos #landiguana

node.text: Photo by @tasneemalsultan / In Saudi Arabia a bride breaks with tradition. Weddings are typically segregated by gender, with a bride making her entrance to a ballroom filled only with female guests who celebrate and dance among themselves. This bride wanted her groom, brothers, father, and uncles to enter minutes before her to see her walk in. After photography, the bride's close male relatives exit to celebrate in another ballroom for men. #riyadh #saudiarabia #weddings
